---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Pagination from '../../components/Pagination.astro';
import VideoCarousel from '../../components/VideoCarousel.jsx';
import ImageCarousel from '../../components/ImageCarousel.jsx';

const base = '/portfolio';

const previous = 'test-board';
const next = null;

const videos = [
  `${base}/videos/MB1.mov`,
  `${base}/videos/MB2.mov`
];

const images = [
  `${base}/images/minibot/1.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/2.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/3.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/4.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/5.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/6.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/7.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/8.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/9.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/10.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/11.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/12.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/13.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/14.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/15.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/16.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/17.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/18.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/19.jpg`,
  `${base}/images/minibot/20.jpg`
];
---

<BaseLayout title="Minibot" base={base}>
  <Pagination
    base={base}
    section="projects"
    listHref={`${base}/projects/robotics`}
    previous={previous}
    next={next}
  />

  <section style="max-width:900px; margin:0 auto; padding:2rem 1rem;">

    <h1>Minibot</h1>

    <h2
      style="
        font-weight: normal;
        color: #555;
        margin-top: 0.5rem;
        font-size: 1.25rem;
      "
    >
      Design a minibot capable of navigating an obstacle course through
      iterative design, fabrication, testing, and continuous improvement.
    </h2>

    <VideoCarousel
      client:load
      videos={videos}
      width="100%"
      height="100%"
    />

    <h2
      style="
        margin-top:2rem;
        border-bottom:2px solid #333;
        padding-bottom:0.5rem;
      "
    >
      Project Overview
    </h2>

    <p>
      The objective of this project was to design and build a compact robot
      capable of completing a challenging obstacle course as quickly and
      reliably as possible. The obstacle course in question had a variety of features, including potholes, weighted doors, and limbo; the obstacles were often adjustable.
      Throughout the process we learned how engineering
      designs evolve through repeated testing and refinement.
      This project definitely tested both our technical and teamwork abilities. In the end, our robot was somewhat successful: It was able to move and be controlled by the controller; however, it could only move while rotating, making it unable to complete the vast majority of the obstacles.
    </p>

    <ImageCarousel client:load images={images} />

    <h2
      style="
        margin-top:2rem;
        border-bottom:2px solid #333;
        padding-bottom:0.5rem;
      "
    >
      Define
    </h2>

    <p>
      Our primary goal was to maximize speed while maintaining reliability
      across all obstacles. However, as the project continued, we became increasingly pressed for time. In the end, we were simply able to create a robot that would react to the controller. However, this reaction does not imply controllability: movement was always associated with rotation, making the robot essentially impossible to control, and by extension, complete the obstacle course. The steps we took to design our robot though were:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Design and fabricate a lightweight and robust wooden drive base.</li>
      <li>Design and lathe a number of hex shafts.</li>
      <li>Write code to allow the robot to be controlled through a RadioLink controller.</li>
      <li>Apply the engineering design process and complete some obstacles!</li>
    </ul>

    <h2
      style="
        margin-top:2rem;
        border-bottom:2px solid #333;
        padding-bottom:0.5rem;
      "
    >
      Concept and CAD Design 
    </h2>

    <p>
      Several drivetrain concepts were explored before selecting the final
      configuration. CAD models were used to verify dimensions for the hex shafts and 3D printed parts, such as the battery case.
      We used these CAD models to futher check wheel
      placement, and component clearances before fabrication began. During
      assembly, adjustments were frequently required to account for real-world
      tolerances and variation in fabrication. We often had to re-lathe our hex shafts, for instance.
    </p>

    <h2
      style="
        margin-top:2rem;
        border-bottom:2px solid #333;
        padding-bottom:0.5rem;
      "
    >
      Test and Iterate
    </h2>

    <p>
      Components were assembled, tested, and modified repeatedly as new issues
      were discovered. This iterative process helped improve overall
      performance while providing valuable experience with mechanical design,
      fabrication, and troubleshooting. One main issue that we consistently saw was that our hex shafts did not cleanly fit with our gearboxes. It took many iterations of lathing hex shafts and slightly adjusting the gearbox for it to fully work in the end.
    </p>

    <p>
      Repeated testing demonstrated the importance (and in fact, neccesity) of validating designs
      experimentally rather than relying solely on theoretical expectations from CAD designs.
    </p>

    <h2
      style="
        margin-top:2rem;
        border-bottom:2px solid #333;
        padding-bottom:0.5rem;
      "
    >
      Final Implementation
    </h2>

    <p>
      Our final robot was not a complete success, neither was it a complete failure. 
      Indeed, our robot was able to be controlled through the RadioLink controller. 
      However, as has been mentioned a few times, it lacked a significant amount of control. 
      This made the robot somewhat inneffective on the obstacle course. We were only able to complete the Limbo, with help from the natural slope of the ground.
    </p>

  </section>
</BaseLayout>